# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: surrealdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:surrealdb/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:surrealdb/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB is a multi-model database built in Rust designed to unify multiple data models into a single engine.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB combines document, graph, relational, time-series, geospatial and key-value data types with powerful search and retrieval functionalities (full-text, vector, hybrid) and real-time and event-driven capabilities, enabling developers to build powerful applications faster and more efficiently.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB can also be used as a backend-as-a-service given its support for end user authentication.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Given that it’s a single Rust binary, SurrealDB can run embedded (in‐app), in the browser (via WebAssembly), in the edge, self-hosted as single backend node, or in a distributed cluster in the cloud.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB is used for data-intensive systems such as applications requiring multiple data types, data layer for AI agents, knowledge graphs, real-time apps (e.g. recommendation engines, fraud detection systems) and embedded/edge systems.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With SurrealDB, you can simplify your database and API infrastructure, reduce development time, and build secure, performant apps quickly and cost-effectively.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] View the features, the latest releases, and documentation.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Getting started with SurrealDB is as easy as starting up the SurrealDB database server, choosing your platform, and integrating its SDK into your code.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] You can easily get started with your platform of choice by reading one of our tutorials.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB is available as a managed cloud service.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Forget about infrastructure operations, monitoring, backups or capacity planning.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB Cloud allows you to focus on building great products using the power and flexibility of SurrealDB in just a few clicks.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Grow from prototype to enterprise-scale.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] The SurrealDB Cloud scalable architecture allows your database to evolve as your application grows, ensuring you are always ahead of demand.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] However if you want to deploy SurrealDB yourself, keep reading below.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB is designed to be simple to install and simple to run - using just one command from your terminal.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] In addition to traditional installation, SurrealDB can be installed and run with HomeBrew, Docker, or using any other container orchestration tool such as Docker Compose, Docker Swarm, Rancher, or in Kubernetes.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] The quickest way to get going with SurrealDB on macOS is to use Homebrew.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] This will install both the command-line tools, and the SurrealDB server as a single executable.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] If you don't use Homebrew, follow the instructions for Linux below to install SurrealDB.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] The easiest and preferred way to get going with SurrealDB on Unix operating systems is to install and use the SurrealDB command-line tool.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Run the following command in your terminal and follow the on-screen instructions.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] The easiest and preferred way to get going with SurrealDB on Windows is to install and use the SurrealDB command-line tool.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Docker can be used to manage and run SurrealDB database instances without the need to install any command-line tools.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] The SurrealDB docker container contains the full command-line tools for importing and exporting data from a running server, or for running a server itself.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] For just getting started with a development server running in memory, you can pass the container a basic initialization to set the user and password as root and enable logging.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With strongly-typed data types, data can be fully modelled right in the database.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Store dynamically computed fields which are calculated when retrieved.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Easily work with unstructured or structured data, in schema-less or schema-full mode.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Connect records together with fully directed graph edge connections.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Query data flexibly with advanced expressions and graph queries.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Store GeoJSON geographical data types, including points, lines and polygons.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Write custom embedded logic using JavaScript functions.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Specify granular access permissions for client and application access.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB combines the database layer, the querying layer, and the API and authentication layer into one platform.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Advanced table-based and row-based customisable access permissions allow for granular data access patterns for different types of users.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] There's no need for custom backend code and security rules with complicated database development.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] As a multi-model database, SurrealDB enables developers to use multiple techniques to store and model data, without having to choose a method in advance.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With the use of tables, SurrealDB has similarities with relational databases, but with the added functionality and flexibility of advanced nested fields and arrays.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Inter-document record links allow for simple to understand and highly-performant related queries without the use of JOINs, eliminating the N+1 query problem.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With full graph database functionality SurrealDB enables more advanced querying and analysis.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Records (or vertices) can be connected to one another with edges, each with its own record properties and metadata.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Simple extensions to traditional SQL queries allow for multi-table, multi-depth document retrieval, efficiently in the database, without the use of complicated JOINs and without bringing the data down to the client.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With SurrealDB, specify your database and API schema in one place, and define column rules and constraints just once.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Once a schema is defined, database access is automatically granted to the relevant users.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] No more custom API code, and no more GraphQL integration.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Simple, flexible, and ready for production in minutes not months.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Connect directly to SurrealDB from any end-user client device.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Run SurrealQL queries directly within web-browsers, ensuring that users can only view or modify the data that they are allowed to access.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Highly-performant WebSocket connections allow for efficient bi-directional queries, responses and notifications.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB is designed to be flexible to use, with support for SurrealQL, GraphQL (coming soon), CRUD support over REST, and JSON-RPC querying and modification over WebSockets.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With direct-to-client connection with in-built permissions, SurrealDB speeds up the development process, and fits in seamlessly into any tech stack.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB keeps every client device in-sync with data modifications pushed in realtime to the clients, applications, end-user devices, and server-side libraries.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Live SQL queries allow for advanced filtering of the changes to which a client subscribes, and efficient data formats, including DIFFing and PATCHing enable highly-performant web-based data syncing.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] SurrealDB can be run as a single in-memory node, or as part of a distributed cluster - offering highly-available and highly-scalable system characteristics.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Designed from the ground up to run in a distributed environment, SurrealDB makes use of special techniques when handling multi-table transactions, and document record IDs - with no use of table or row locks.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Embedded JavaScript functions allow for advanced, custom functionality, with computation logic being moved to the data layer.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] This improves upon the traditional approach of moving data to the client devices before applying any computation logic, ensuring that only the necessary data is transferred remotely.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] These advanced JavaScript functions, with support for the ES2020 standard, allow any developer to analyse the data in ever more simple-yet-advanced ways.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Built entirely in Rust as a single library, SurrealDB is designed to be used as both an embedded database library with advanced querying functionality, and as a database server which can operate in a distributed cluster.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] With low memory usage and cpu requirements, the system requirements have been specifically thought through for running in all types of environment.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Join our growing community around the world, for help, ideas, and discussions regarding SurrealDB.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] We would for you to get involved with SurrealDB development!
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] If you wish to help, you can learn more about how you can contribute to this project in the contribution guide.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] For security issues, view our vulnerability policy, view our Trust and Security page, and kindly email us at security@surrealdb.com instead of posting a public issue on GitHub.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] Source code for SurrealDB is variously licensed under a number of different licenses.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] A copy of each license can be found in each repository.
[src:surrealdb/main-readme-md] For more information, see the licensing information.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] In the field of database design, a **multi-model database** is a database management system designed to support multiple data models against a single, integrated backend.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] In contrast, most database management systems are organized around a single data model that determines how data can be organized, stored, and manipulated.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Document, graph, relational, and key–value models are examples of data models that may be supported by a multi-model database.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] The relational data model became popular after its publication by Edgar F.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Due to increasing requirements for horizontal scalability and fault tolerance, NoSQL databases became prominent after 2009.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] NoSQL databases use a variety of data models, with document, graph, and key–value models being popular.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] A multi-model database is a database that can store, index and query data in more than one model.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] For some time, databases have primarily supported only one model, such as: relational database, document-oriented database, graph database or triplestore.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] A database that combines many of these is multi-model.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] This should not be confused with multimodal database systems such as Pixeltable or ApertureDB, which focus on unified management of different media types (images, video, audio, text) rather than different data models.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] For some time, it was all but forgotten (or considered irrelevant) that there were any other database models besides relational.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] The relational model and notion of third normal form were the default standard for all data storage.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] However, prior to the dominance of relational data modeling, from about 1980 to 2005, the hierarchical database model was commonly used.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Since 2000 or 2010, many NoSQL models that are non-relational, including documents, triples, key–value stores and graphs are popular.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Arguably, geospatial data, temporal data, and text data are also separate models, though indexed, queryable text data is generally termed a "search engine" rather than a database.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] The first time the word "multi-model" has been associated to the databases was on May 30, 2012 in Cologne, Germany, during the Luca Garulli's key note "*NoSQL Adoption – What’s the Next Step?*".
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Luca Garulli envisioned the evolution of the 1st generation NoSQL products into new products with more features able to be used by multiple use cases.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] The idea of multi-model databases can be traced back to Object–Relational Data Management Systems (ORDBMS) in the early 1990s and in a more broader scope even to federated and integrated DBMSs in the early 1980s.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] An ORDBMS system manages different types of data such as relational, object, text and spatial by plugging domain specific data types, functions and index implementations into the DBMS kernels.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] A multi-model database is most directly a response to the "polyglot persistence" approach of knitting together multiple database products, each handing a different model, to achieve a multi-model capability as described by Martin Fowler.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] This strategy has two major disadvantages: it leads to a significant increase in operational complexity, and there is no support for maintaining data consistency across the separate data stores, so multi-model databases have begun to fill in this gap.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Multi-model databases are intended to offer the data modeling advantages of polyglot persistence, without its disadvantages.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Operational complexity, in particular, is reduced through the use of a single data store.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] As more and more platforms are proposed to deal with multi-model data, there are a few works on benchmarking multi-model databases.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] For instance, Pluciennik, Oliveira, and UniBench reviewed existing multi-model databases and made an evaluation effort towards comparing multi-model databases and other SQL and NoSQL databases respectively.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] 2. they can employ a unified query language such as AQL, Orient SQL, SQL/XML, SQL/JSON to retrieve correlated multi-model data, such as graph-JSON-key/value, XML-relational, and JSON-relational in a single platform.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] 3. they are able to support multi-model ACID transactions in the stand-alone mode.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] The main difference between the available multi-model databases is related to their architectures.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Multi-model databases can support different models either within the engine or via different layers on top of the engine.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Some products may provide an engine which supports documents and graphs while others provide layers on top of a key-key store.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] With a layered architecture, each data model is provided via its own component.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] In addition to offering multiple data models in a single data store, some databases allow developers to easily define custom data models.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] This capability is enabled by ACID transactions with high performance and scalability.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] In order for a custom data model to support concurrent updates, the database must be able to synchronize updates across multiple keys.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] ACID transactions, if they are sufficiently performant, allow such synchronization.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] JSON documents, graphs, and relational tables can all be implemented in a manner that inherits the horizontal scalability and fault-tolerance of the underlying data store.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] The traditional theory of relations is not enough to accurately describe multi-model database systems.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Recent research is focused on developing a new theoretical foundation for these systems.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] Category theory can provide a unified, rigorous language for modeling, integrating, and transforming different data models.
[src:surrealdb/multi-model-database] By representing multi-model data as sets and their relationships as functions or relations within the Set category, we can create a formal framework to describe, manipulate, and understand various data models and how they interact.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:surrealdb/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:surrealdb/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:surrealdb/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:surrealdb/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] SurrealDB is a multi-model database built in Rust designed to unify multiple data models into a single, powerful engine.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] Common SurrealDB use cases include AI agents, knowledge graphs, real-time apps (e.g. recommendation engines, fraud detection systems), and any other type of application requiring multiple data types.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] SurrealDB can also be used as a backend-as-a-service (BaaS) thanks to its support for direct user authentication.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] Given that it’s a single Rust binary, SurrealDB can also run embedded (in‐app), in the browser (via WebAssembly), in the edge, as single backend node, or in a distributed cluster.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] SurrealDB is source-available (see the code here on GitHub) and is also available as a cloud managed service through SurrealDB Cloud.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] More information can be found in our features page.
[src:surrealdb/surrealdb] More companies and an overview of the benefits provided by SurrealDB can be found in our case studies page.
[src:surrealdb/surrealql] SurrealQL is SurrealDB's query language.
[src:surrealdb/surrealql] Syntax is broadly SQL-like, with extensions for nested fields, graph edges, record IDs, and other SurrealDB-specific constructs.
[src:surrealdb/surrealql] For a guided introduction, see Learn: Querying.
[src:surrealdb/surrealql] Further detail is organised under Statements and the other sections in this reference.
